The idea of so simple and easy a solution did not, it would seem, strike any of Wyclif's contemporaries; and he himself, though coming nearest to it in my opinion, does not quite hit the mark. Some of them affirmed that such propositions were neither false nor true (p. 194. l. 24—37). Some, that they were both true and false (p. 194, l. 38 to p. 195, l. 14). OtherS‚ that they were in reality exceptive propositionS, as no proposition can include itself in its own meaning (p. 195, 1. 14 to p. 196, l. 20). Some said that the words implied contradiction if under- stood as they were, but they did not explain how they were to be un- derstood otherwise (p. 196, l. 20 to p. 197, l. 20). And others again denied that such words as proposition, true, false, &C.‚ could receive universal extension (p. 197, l. 20 to p. 199, l. 9). Several other opinions are enumerated besides (pp. 199—203).
